When any arg to a subcommand starts with `--` and is not a recognized flag for that subcommand, the CLI prints "unknown flag: --XYZ" with exit code 1 and does NOT dispatch the subcommand. This prevents silent misinterpretation where a mistyped or unsupported long flag would be treated as a positional argument (e.g. `drift diff --all` must NOT parse `--all` as a hash — it is a recognized flag for diff, see diff_all). Recognized long flags per subcommand: `--help` for all subcommands; `--verbose` for list only; `--all` for diff only; `--dry-run` for reset, link, and unlink only. Any other `--foo` is rejected. Short flags follow the same rule: `-h` is recognized for all subcommands; any other `-x` short flag is rejected as "unknown flag: -x". This check runs AFTER the help_flag check, so `--help` is always honored even on subcommands where it is the only recognized flag. NOTE: The global flags --json, --no-color, and --color= are stripped by the global_flag_stripping pre-pass BEFORE this check runs, so they never trigger unknown_flag_rejection. See <ref spec="output.global_flag_stripping">global flag stripping</ref> and principles.specs_are_truth.